/* cloud+ :: content/domain5.js — lazy-loaded reading module for CV0-004 Domain 5 (DevOps Fundamentals, deep). */
window.CLOUDPLUS = window.CLOUDPLUS || {}; CLOUDPLUS.reading = CLOUDPLUS.reading || {};
CLOUDPLUS.reading[5] = [];
CLOUDPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Source Control and Version Management Fundamentals", body:"<p><span class='keyterm'>Version control</span> (also called source control) is the discipline of recording every change to a body of code or configuration over time so that any prior state can be recovered, compared, and audited. In a cloud DevOps practice it is the single source of truth: infrastructure-as-code, application source, pipeline definitions, dashboards, and even runbooks all live in the same kind of repository. Without version control there is no reliable way to answer the three questions that dominate every incident review — what changed, when, and who changed it — and there is no safe way for many engineers to work on the same system at once. Version control is therefore not an optional convenience; it is the substrate on which every other DevOps practice in this domain is built, and the exam treats fluency with its vocabulary as a baseline expectation.</p><h3>Centralized versus distributed</h3><p>Historically, version control was <em>centralized</em>: tools like Subversion (SVN) and CVS kept the authoritative history on one server, and each developer checked out a working copy. The weakness is obvious — if the server is down, no one can commit, branch, or even view history. The dominant tool today is <span class='keyterm'>Git</span>, a <span class='keyterm'>distributed version control system</span> in which every developer holds a complete copy of the entire history, not just a snapshot. This distributed model means work continues offline, branching and history inspection are local and instantaneous, and there is no single point of failure for the history itself. A remote like GitHub, GitLab, or Bitbucket still acts as a coordination hub, but it is a convenience for collaboration, not a dependency for everyday work. If the remote vanished, every clone could rebuild it.</p><h3>The core operations</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>commit</span> is an atomic snapshot of staged changes together with author, timestamp, and a message; each commit is identified by a SHA-1 (or, increasingly, SHA-256) hash and points to its parent, forming an immutable chain. Because each hash is computed from the content plus the parent hash, history cannot be silently rewritten without changing every downstream identifier — this is what gives Git its tamper-evidence and is why Git underpins audit-grade change tracking. A <span class='keyterm'>push</span> uploads local commits to a remote so teammates can see them; a <span class='keyterm'>pull</span> (a fetch followed by a merge) brings remote commits down into your local copy. A <span class='keyterm'>merge</span> combines the history of two branches into one, producing a merge commit when the branches have diverged. The staging area, or <em>index</em>, is a distinctive Git concept: changes must be staged with <code>git add</code> before they become part of a commit, which lets you craft focused, reviewable commits out of a messy working directory.</p><p>A typical first-change workflow looks like this:</p><pre><code>git clone https://git.example.com/team/app.git\ncd app\ngit checkout -b feature/add-metrics\n# edit files...\ngit add metrics.py config.yaml\ngit status                       # confirm what is staged\ngit commit -m 'Add request-latency metric'\ngit push -u origin feature/add-metrics</code></pre><p>The <code>git status</code> and <code>git diff</code> commands let you inspect what is staged versus merely modified before you commit, while <code>git log --oneline --graph --all</code> renders the branch topology as an ASCII graph. When you make a mistake, <code>git revert &lt;sha&gt;</code> creates a <em>new</em> commit that undoes a previous one — safe on shared history — whereas <code>git reset --hard &lt;sha&gt;</code> moves the branch pointer and discards work, which is dangerous on a branch others have pulled. Knowing which to use is a frequent source of both real-world accidents and exam questions, because the two look similar but have opposite safety profiles.</p><h3>Why version management matters in the cloud</h3><p>When servers are cattle, not pets, the definition of a server lives in a repository, not on a disk. Rolling back a bad deployment becomes <code>git revert</code> followed by a pipeline run rather than a frantic midnight manual restore. Auditors can answer who changed what, when, and why directly from <code>git blame</code> and the commit log, which is invaluable for compliance frameworks that demand change traceability. Tagging a release with <code>git tag -a v2.4.0 -m 'Release 2.4.0'</code> creates a permanent, named pointer that build systems reference to produce reproducible artifacts; semantic version tags in the form <code>MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH</code> communicate the nature of a change to consumers at a glance. Finally, because configuration and infrastructure now live in Git too, the version-control system becomes the control plane for the entire environment — the foundation of the GitOps model explored later in this domain.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Operation</th><th>Command</th><th>Effect</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Snapshot locally</td><td>git commit</td><td>Records staged changes</td></tr><tr><td>Send to remote</td><td>git push</td><td>Uploads local commits</td></tr><tr><td>Retrieve remote</td><td>git pull / git fetch</td><td>Brings down remote commits</td></tr><tr><td>Combine branches</td><td>git merge</td><td>Joins two histories</td></tr><tr><td>Undo (safe)</td><td>git revert</td><td>New commit that reverses</td></tr><tr><td>Move pointer (risky)</td><td>git reset</td><td>Rewrites local history</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>EXAM TIP</div>Know the verbs cold: commit saves locally, push sends to the remote, pull/fetch retrieves, merge combines branches, revert creates a new undoing commit, and reset moves the branch pointer. The exam often hides the right answer behind a precise definition of one of these, and distinguishing revert (safe on shared branches) from reset (rewrites history) is a classic trap.</div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Branching Models, Code Review, and Pull Requests", body:"<p>A <span class='keyterm'>branch</span> is simply a movable pointer to a commit, which makes parallel lines of development almost free in Git. Creating a branch records a new reference; it does not copy files, so even a multi-gigabyte repository branches instantly. <span class='keyterm'>Branch management</span> is the set of conventions a team adopts to keep those parallel lines coherent, to minimize painful merges, and to keep the mainline always releasable. Poor branch hygiene — long-lived branches that drift far from the trunk — is one of the most common causes of integration pain, while disciplined branching is the quiet enabler of fast, safe delivery. The exam expects you to know the two dominant models and the mechanics of review.</p><h3>Two dominant branching models</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>GitFlow</span> uses long-lived <code>main</code> and <code>develop</code> branches plus short-lived <code>feature/</code>, <code>release/</code>, and <code>hotfix/</code> branches. New work branches from <code>develop</code>; when a release is ready, a <code>release/</code> branch is cut for stabilization, then merged into both <code>main</code> (and tagged) and back into <code>develop</code>. Urgent production fixes branch from <code>main</code> as <code>hotfix/</code> and merge back to both. GitFlow suits products with scheduled, versioned releases — desktop software, firmware, on-prem appliances — but it adds ceremony and encourages branches to live long enough to diverge. <span class='keyterm'>Trunk-based development</span> keeps almost everything on a single <code>main</code> trunk with very short-lived feature branches merged within a day or two, often hidden behind <span class='keyterm'>feature flags</span> so incomplete work can ship dark and be enabled later. It pairs naturally with continuous delivery because the trunk is always releasable, and because branches are tiny, merge conflicts are rare and small.</p><h3>Creating and integrating branches</h3><pre><code>git switch -c feature/oauth-login   # create and switch\n# ...work and commit...\ngit fetch origin\ngit rebase origin/main              # replay your work atop latest main\ngit push --force-with-lease         # update the feature branch safely</code></pre><p>Rebasing replays your commits on top of the latest mainline, producing a clean linear history that is easy to read and to bisect when hunting a regression; merging instead preserves the exact topology of when work happened, which some teams prefer for auditability. The <code>--force-with-lease</code> flag refuses to overwrite the remote if someone else has pushed in the meantime, preventing the classic lost-work accident of a plain <code>--force</code>. A common rule of thumb is to rebase your own private feature branch to keep it tidy, but never rebase a branch others have already based work on, because rewriting shared history forces everyone else into painful recovery.</p><h3>Resolving merge conflicts</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>merge conflict</span> occurs when two branches change the same lines of the same file in incompatible ways. Git cannot guess which version is correct, so it pauses the merge and marks the file with conflict markers:</p><pre><code>&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; HEAD\nmax_connections = 200\n=======\nmax_connections = 500\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; feature/scale-pool</code></pre><p>The engineer edits the file to the correct combined result, removes the markers, then runs <code>git add</code> and <code>git commit</code> to complete the merge. Frequent integration — the heart of CI — keeps conflicts small and easy to resolve, which is the practical argument for short-lived branches and a major reason trunk-based teams suffer fewer merge headaches.</p><h3>Code review through pull requests</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>pull request</span> (PR), called a merge request on GitLab, is a formal proposal to merge one branch into another. It is the social and technical hub of <span class='keyterm'>code review</span>: reviewers read the diff, leave line-level comments, request changes, and ultimately approve. Most teams enforce <em>branch protection</em> so that <code>main</code> can only be updated through a PR that has at least one approval and a passing pipeline, which converts code review from an optional courtesy into a hard gate. Effective review checks for correctness, security, readability, test coverage, and adherence to standards, and modern PRs can also require status checks like a green build and a passing security scan before the merge button unlocks. Because the PR carries the full discussion thread, it becomes durable documentation of <em>why</em> a change was made, complementing the commit log's record of <em>what</em> changed.</p><h3>Merge strategies and a healthy review culture</h3><p>When a PR is approved, the platform offers several ways to integrate it. A plain <em>merge commit</em> preserves every individual commit plus a merge node, keeping the full granular history. A <em>squash merge</em> collapses all of the branch's commits into one tidy commit on the trunk, which keeps mainline history clean and readable at the cost of the fine-grained detail. A <em>rebase merge</em> replays the commits onto the trunk with no merge node, producing a strictly linear history. Many trunk-based teams prefer squash merges so that each PR maps to exactly one mainline commit that is trivial to revert as a unit. Beyond mechanics, healthy review culture keeps PRs small (a few hundred lines at most), responds quickly so authors are not blocked, separates blocking concerns from optional suggestions, and uses automated linters and formatters so humans spend their attention on logic and design rather than on style nits a machine could catch.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Aspect</th><th>GitFlow</th><th>Trunk-Based</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Long-lived branches</td><td>main + develop</td><td>main only</td></tr><tr><td>Feature branch life</td><td>Days to weeks</td><td>Hours to a day</td></tr><tr><td>Release cadence</td><td>Scheduled / versioned</td><td>Continuous</td></tr><tr><td>Merge conflict risk</td><td>Higher</td><td>Lower</td></tr><tr><td>Incomplete work</td><td>Stays on branch</td><td>Hidden by feature flags</td></tr><tr><td>Best fit</td><td>Versioned products</td><td>SaaS / CD</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>SCENARIO</div>A team ships to production several times a day but suffers painful weekly merges from a long-lived integration branch. The fix is to move toward trunk-based development: tiny feature branches, frequent merges to main behind feature flags, and a PR gate enforcing at least one review plus a passing build before merge.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>EXAM TIP</div>Associate GitFlow with scheduled, versioned releases and multiple long-lived branches; associate trunk-based development with continuous delivery, short-lived branches, and feature flags. A pull request is the mechanism that enforces code review, and branch protection is what makes the review mandatory rather than optional.</div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"CI/CD Pipelines: Concepts and Workflow", body:"<p><span class='keyterm'>Continuous integration</span> (CI) is the practice of merging every developer's work into a shared mainline frequently — ideally many times a day — and verifying each merge with an automated build and test run. The goal is to surface integration problems while they are still small. <span class='keyterm'>Continuous delivery</span> (CD) extends this so that every change which passes the pipeline is automatically packaged and made deployable at the push of a button; <span class='keyterm'>continuous deployment</span> goes one step further and pushes every passing change to production with no manual gate at all. Together these practices form the automated assembly line that turns a commit into running software, replacing the slow, error-prone, weekend-long manual release processes of the past with a repeatable, auditable flow.</p><h3>The canonical workflow</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>pipeline</span> is a sequence of <em>stages</em>, each composed of <em>jobs</em> that run automatically when triggered, usually by a push or a pull request via a webhook. The classic ordering is: <strong>source</strong> (a webhook fires on commit), <strong>build</strong> (compile and assemble), <strong>test</strong> (unit, then integration, then end-to-end), <strong>security</strong> (scanning), <strong>package</strong> (produce artifacts), and <strong>deploy</strong> (release to an environment). Each stage acts as a quality gate: failure halts the line and notifies the team, embodying the principle of <em>failing fast</em>. The economic logic is that defects grow more expensive the later they are caught, so the pipeline is deliberately arranged to catch each class of problem at the earliest, cheapest possible moment.</p><h3>Automation, integration, and feedback</h3><p>The defining property of CI is <span class='keyterm'>automation</span>: no step requires a human to remember to run it. <span class='keyterm'>Code integration</span> means changes are combined and validated continuously rather than in a big-bang merge at the end of a sprint, which is how teams avoid the dreaded integration hell where weeks of divergent work must be reconciled at once under deadline pressure. Fast, deterministic pipelines give developers feedback within minutes, so defects are caught while the context is still fresh in the author's mind — a ten-minute pipeline that breaks the build is a minor interruption, while the same defect found in production a week later becomes a paging incident with customer impact.</p><blockquote>If it is not automated, it is not continuous. A pipeline that requires a human to click between every stage is a checklist, not a CI/CD system.</blockquote><h3>Reproducibility and ephemeral runners</h3><p>Pipelines encode <span class='keyterm'>idempotency</span> and reproducibility: given the same commit, the pipeline should produce the same artifact every time. This is why builds pin dependency versions, run in clean ephemeral runners rather than on a developer's machine, and forbid network access to unpinned sources during the build. The <em>build once, deploy many</em> principle follows directly — the artifact produced in the build stage is the exact one promoted to staging and then production, so the thing tested is the thing released, with no chance of an environment-specific rebuild introducing a difference.</p><h3>Deployment strategies</h3><p>The deploy stage is where several risk-reduction strategies appear, and the exam expects you to match each to its defining trait. A <span class='keyterm'>blue-green deployment</span> runs two identical environments and switches traffic from the old (blue) to the new (green) all at once, giving instant rollback by simply switching back. A <span class='keyterm'>canary deployment</span> routes a small percentage of traffic to the new version first, watches metrics and error rates, and ramps up only if the new version stays healthy. A <span class='keyterm'>rolling deployment</span> replaces instances a few at a time so capacity is preserved, while a <em>recreate</em> strategy stops the old version entirely before starting the new one, accepting downtime for simplicity. Each trades speed, cost, and blast radius differently, and the right choice depends on how much spare capacity you can pay for and how quickly you must be able to undo a bad release.</p><h3>Environments and promotion</h3><p>A pipeline rarely deploys straight to production. Instead a change is <em>promoted</em> through a series of <span class='keyterm'>environments</span> that grow progressively more production-like: a developer's local environment, then a shared development or integration environment, then staging (a faithful mirror of production used for final validation and performance testing), and finally production itself. The exact same artifact moves through each, gated by automated tests and, in a continuous-delivery model, by a human approval before the production step. Keeping environments configured identically — same OS, same dependency versions, same infrastructure shape, differing only in scale and secrets — is what makes a green staging run a trustworthy predictor of production behavior. Configuration that differs between environments (database URLs, feature flags, credentials) is injected at deploy time rather than baked into the artifact, preserving the build-once principle.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Strategy</th><th>How it works</th><th>Rollback</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Blue-green</td><td>Two full environments, flip traffic</td><td>Instant (flip back)</td></tr><tr><td>Canary</td><td>Small % first, then ramp</td><td>Stop ramp / reroute</td></tr><tr><td>Rolling</td><td>Replace instances gradually</td><td>Roll back batches</td></tr><tr><td>Recreate</td><td>Stop old, start new</td><td>Redeploy old (downtime)</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout'><div class='lbl'>NOTE</div>The distinction the exam loves: continuous <em>delivery</em> stops at a deployable artifact awaiting an approval to release, while continuous <em>deployment</em> releases automatically with no human gate. Many regulated environments deliberately choose delivery to retain a documented change-approval step.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>EXAM TIP</div>Order matters. Cheap, fast tests (unit) run before expensive ones (end-to-end), and security scanning is woven in rather than bolted on at the end. If a question asks where a failure should stop the line, the answer is the earliest stage that can detect it. And match the deployment strategy to the requirement: instant rollback points to blue-green, gradual exposure with metric watching points to canary.</div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Building a Pipeline: A GitHub Actions Example", body:"<p>To make the workflow concrete, consider a pipeline expressed as a <span class='keyterm'>GitHub Actions</span> workflow file. The file lives in the repository under <code>.github/workflows/</code>, so the pipeline is versioned alongside the code it builds — a change to the pipeline goes through the same review and history as a change to the application itself. This is sometimes called <span class='keyterm'>pipeline-as-code</span>, and it is a defining trait of modern CI/CD: the build process is no longer a fragile set of clicks in a server GUI that only one engineer understands, but a reviewable, diffable, version-controlled text file that the whole team can read and improve.</p><h3>A complete workflow</h3><p>The workflow below builds a Python service, runs its tests, scans dependencies for known vulnerabilities, and builds and pushes a container image only when both prior jobs succeed.</p><pre><code>name: ci-cd\non:\n  push:\n    branches: [ main ]\n  pull_request:\njobs:\n  build-test:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n      - uses: actions/setup-python@v5\n        with:\n          python-version: '3.12'\n      - run: pip install -r requirements.txt\n      - run: pytest --maxfail=1 --disable-warnings\n  security-scan:\n    needs: build-test\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n      - run: pip install pip-audit\n      - run: pip-audit -r requirements.txt\n  package:\n    needs: [ build-test, security-scan ]\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n      - run: docker build -t registry.example.com/app:${{ github.sha }} .\n      - run: docker push registry.example.com/app:${{ github.sha }}</code></pre><h3>Reading the file</h3><p>The <code>on:</code> block is the <span class='keyterm'>trigger</span>: this pipeline runs on every push to <code>main</code> and on every pull request, so contributors get feedback before their work is merged. Each entry under <code>jobs:</code> runs in its own clean runner, in parallel by default. The <code>needs:</code> key creates an explicit dependency graph, so <code>package</code> cannot run unless both <code>build-test</code> and <code>security-scan</code> pass first; this is how the quality gate is enforced declaratively rather than by hopeful convention. Tagging the image with <code>github.sha</code> ties the artifact to the exact commit that produced it, giving end-to-end traceability from a running container in production all the way back to a single line of source code.</p><h3>Runners, secrets, and environments</h3><p>Jobs execute on <em>runners</em>, which are ephemeral VMs or containers; GitHub hosts a managed fleet, but teams can register <em>self-hosted runners</em> when they need special hardware, a private network, or a licensed toolchain. Using clean runners guarantees the build does not depend on leftover state from a previous run, which is essential for reproducibility. Credentials such as the registry password are injected as encrypted <em>secrets</em> referenced like <code>${{ secrets.REGISTRY_TOKEN }}</code> and are never hard-coded into the YAML or printed to logs. Deployment jobs target named <em>environments</em> that can require manual approval, enforce wait timers, or restrict which branches may deploy — this is the mechanism by which continuous <em>delivery</em> keeps a human gate while everything before it stays automated.</p><h3>How other engines compare</h3><p>The same conceptual structure appears across CI engines; only the syntax differs. A Jenkins <code>Jenkinsfile</code> uses a <code>pipeline { stages { stage('Build') { ... } } }</code> block; GitLab CI uses a <code>.gitlab-ci.yml</code> with top-level <code>stages</code> and per-job <code>script</code> keys; Azure Pipelines uses an <code>azure-pipelines.yml</code>. Once you can read one, you can read them all, because they share the same vocabulary of triggers, stages, jobs, dependencies, artifacts, and secrets. Recognizing that vocabulary in unfamiliar YAML is exactly the skill the exam is testing.</p><h3>Caching, matrices, and artifacts between jobs</h3><p>Real pipelines add a few more capabilities worth recognizing. <em>Caching</em> stores expensive-to-rebuild directories — a dependency cache, a compiler cache — between runs so that an unchanged dependency list is restored in seconds instead of re-downloaded every time, dramatically shortening feedback. A <em>matrix</em> strategy runs the same job across several combinations of inputs in parallel; testing against Python 3.11, 3.12, and 3.13 at once, for example, catches version-specific breakage without writing three nearly identical jobs. Because each job runs on its own clean runner with no shared filesystem, anything one job produces that a later job needs — a compiled binary, a coverage report, a built image reference — must be passed explicitly as an <em>artifact</em> using an upload step in the producing job and a download step in the consuming job. Understanding that jobs are isolated by default explains why <code>needs</code> alone is not enough to share files: ordering and data transfer are separate concerns. Pipelines also commonly fan out work across jobs, run conditional steps based on the branch or the event type, and reuse shared logic through composite or reusable workflows so that dozens of repositories inherit one maintained build definition rather than copying it.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Engine</th><th>Definition file</th><th>Hosting</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>GitHub Actions</td><td>.github/workflows/*.yml</td><td>Hosted (or self-hosted runners)</td></tr><tr><td>Jenkins</td><td>Jenkinsfile</td><td>Self-hosted</td></tr><tr><td>GitLab CI</td><td>.gitlab-ci.yml</td><td>Hosted or self-hosted</td></tr><tr><td>Azure Pipelines</td><td>azure-pipelines.yml</td><td>Hosted</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>EXAM TIP</div>You will not write YAML on the exam, but you must be able to read it: identify the trigger (the <code>on</code> block), recognize that <code>needs</code> / <code>depends_on</code> orders jobs into a graph, and understand that secrets are injected at runtime, never committed. A hard-coded password or API key in a pipeline file is a security finding, not a feature.</div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"DevSecOps: Shifting Security Left in the Pipeline", body:"<p><span class='keyterm'>DevSecOps</span> is the integration of security practices directly into the CI/CD pipeline rather than treating security as a final, separate review performed by a different team after development is finished. The guiding metaphor is <span class='keyterm'>shift left</span>: move security checks as early in the timeline as possible, because a vulnerability caught in a pull request costs minutes to fix, while the same flaw caught in production can cost a full incident response, customer notification, and regulatory exposure. Automation is what makes this scalable — a human cannot manually review every commit for injection flaws or leaked secrets, but a scanner can run on every push without fatigue or complaint, turning security from a periodic audit into a continuous property of the pipeline.</p><h3>The classes of automated security testing</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>SAST</span> (static application security testing) analyzes source code without running it, catching issues like SQL-injection patterns, unsafe deserialization, and hard-coded secrets. Because it needs only the code, it runs early, on the pull request. <span class='keyterm'>DAST</span> (dynamic application security testing) probes a <em>running</em> instance from the outside for exploitable behavior such as cross-site scripting or broken authentication; it therefore runs later, against a deployed test environment, after the application is actually up. <span class='keyterm'>SCA</span> (software composition analysis) inventories third-party dependencies and flags known-vulnerable versions from databases like the CVE list and the National Vulnerability Database — critical because modern applications are mostly composed of open-source dependencies rather than first-party code. <span class='keyterm'>IaC scanning</span> inspects Terraform, CloudFormation, or Kubernetes manifests for misconfigurations such as a publicly readable storage bucket or an over-permissive security group <em>before</em> they are ever provisioned, while <span class='keyterm'>container image scanning</span> checks the OS packages baked into an image for known CVEs.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Scan type</th><th>What it inspects</th><th>Catches</th><th>Pipeline stage</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>SAST</td><td>Source code (not running)</td><td>Injection, secrets in code</td><td>Build / PR</td></tr><tr><td>SCA</td><td>Dependencies</td><td>Vulnerable libraries (CVEs)</td><td>Build</td></tr><tr><td>IaC scan</td><td>Terraform / k8s YAML</td><td>Misconfigurations</td><td>Build</td></tr><tr><td>DAST</td><td>Running application</td><td>XSS, auth flaws, runtime issues</td><td>Test / staging</td></tr><tr><td>Image scan</td><td>Container images</td><td>OS-level CVEs</td><td>Package</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Adding security as a gated job</h3><p>In practice, each scan is just another pipeline job that fails the build when it finds a high-severity issue. The job below runs a SAST scan only after the build succeeds, so a code-level vulnerability blocks the merge instead of slipping through:</p><pre><code>  sast-scan:\n    needs: build-test\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n      - run: pip install semgrep\n      - run: semgrep --config auto --error</code></pre><p>The <code>--error</code> flag is what turns the scan into a gate: a finding sets a non-zero exit code, which fails the job and stops the pipeline before the change can be merged or deployed. Without that flag the scan would report findings but let the build pass — a common misconfiguration that quietly defeats the whole purpose.</p><h3>Secrets management and the supply chain</h3><p>A central DevSecOps concern is keeping secrets out of source control entirely. Pipelines pull credentials from a <span class='keyterm'>secrets vault</span> such as HashiCorp Vault, AWS Secrets Manager, or Azure Key Vault at runtime and pass them as environment variables; pre-commit hooks and dedicated secret scanners catch accidental commits of API keys before they reach the remote, and if a secret does leak it must be <em>rotated</em>, not merely deleted from history, because the old value may already have been copied. The integrity of the <span class='keyterm'>software supply chain</span> matters just as much: signing artifacts so consumers can verify their origin, and generating a <span class='keyterm'>software bill of materials</span> (SBOM) that enumerates every component, lets downstream users verify exactly what they are running and respond quickly when a new CVE lands in a dependency they use.</p><h3>Culture, gates, and risk-based response</h3><p>DevSecOps is as much a cultural shift as a tooling one: security becomes a shared responsibility of the whole delivery team rather than a gate owned by an outside group that developers try to route around. That cultural change only sticks if the automated checks are tuned to be useful — a scanner that floods every PR with hundreds of low-severity or false-positive findings trains engineers to ignore it, defeating the purpose. Mature programs therefore apply <em>risk-based</em> gating: block the merge only on high-severity, exploitable findings, while logging lower-severity items to a backlog for scheduled remediation. They also distinguish a true positive from a false positive and from an accepted risk, recording explicit exceptions with an owner and an expiry rather than silently suppressing alerts. The end state is a pipeline where passing the build is a credible statement that the change met the organization's security bar, not merely that it compiled. This is reinforced by least-privilege pipeline credentials, signed commits, and an audit trail that ties every deployed artifact back to a reviewed, scanned, and approved change.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>SCENARIO</div>A nightly DAST scan repeatedly finds the same reflected-XSS flaw days after each release. The DevSecOps remedy is to add a SAST rule and a targeted unit test to the pull-request pipeline so the entire class of bug is blocked at merge time, shifting detection left from staging to the PR and breaking the costly find-late, fix-late cycle.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>EXAM TIP</div>Match the acronym to the timing and input: SAST and SCA need only the code or its dependency list and run early; DAST needs a deployed, running target and therefore runs later against a test environment. Secrets always come from a vault at runtime — a credential committed to a repo is a finding regardless of how the repo is protected.</div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Artifacts and Repositories", body:"<p>An <span class='keyterm'>artifact</span> is the deployable output of a build: the concrete thing the pipeline produces and stores so it can later be deployed without rebuilding. Treating the artifact as a first-class, immutable object is central to reliable delivery. The <em>build once, deploy many</em> principle says you build an artifact a single time, store it, and then promote that exact same artifact through testing, staging, and production — because rebuilding for each environment risks producing subtly different binaries (a different dependency version pulled in, a different base image, a different compiler patch) and thereby testing something other than what you ultimately ship. Artifacts fall into a few recognizable families that the exam expects you to distinguish precisely.</p><h3>Images: VM and container</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Images</span> come in two forms that are easy to confuse. A <em>VM image</em> — such as an AWS AMI, an Azure managed image, or a VMware template — is a full machine snapshot including the operating system, drivers, and any baked-in software; it is used to boot a complete virtual machine and is correspondingly large, often several gigabytes, and slow to start. A <em>container image</em> is a layered, lightweight bundle of an application plus only its runtime dependencies, run by an engine like Docker on a host whose kernel is shared among many containers; it is far smaller, sometimes only tens of megabytes, and starts in seconds. The practical difference is granularity and weight: you provision a VM image to get a whole server, but you run dozens of container images side by side on one server.</p><h3>Packages and flat files</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Packages</span> bundle software for an operating system's package manager. <code>RPM</code> is the format for Red Hat Enterprise Linux, CentOS, Fedora, and their derivatives, managed by <code>yum</code> or <code>dnf</code>. <code>Debian</code> packages (<code>.deb</code>) serve Debian and Ubuntu, managed by <code>apt</code>. These formats carry metadata, dependency declarations, and install/remove scripts, so the package manager can resolve dependencies automatically and cleanly uninstall software later. Simpler archive formats also appear as artifacts: <code>ZIP</code> and <code>tar</code> (often gzip-compressed to <code>.tar.gz</code> or <code>.tgz</code>) merely group files for transport with no install logic at all. A <span class='keyterm'>flat file</span> artifact is a single self-contained deliverable — a compiled static binary, a Java JAR, or a lone configuration file — with no installer wrapper, simply copied into place.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Artifact</th><th>Type</th><th>Typical use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>AMI / template</td><td>VM image</td><td>Boot a virtual machine</td></tr><tr><td>Container image</td><td>Container image</td><td>Run via Docker / Kubernetes</td></tr><tr><td>RPM</td><td>Package</td><td>Install on RHEL / CentOS / Fedora</td></tr><tr><td>Debian (.deb)</td><td>Package</td><td>Install on Debian / Ubuntu</td></tr><tr><td>ZIP / tar(.gz)</td><td>Archive</td><td>Bundle files for transfer</td></tr><tr><td>Binary / JAR / config</td><td>Flat file</td><td>Drop-in deliverable</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Repositories: where artifacts live</h3><p>Artifacts are stored in an <span class='keyterm'>artifact repository</span> or registry — a Docker registry such as Docker Hub or Amazon ECR, an APT or YUM mirror, a language index like npm or PyPI, or a general-purpose tool like JFrog Artifactory or Sonatype Nexus. Repositories are either <span class='keyterm'>public</span> or <span class='keyterm'>private</span>. A public repository is open to the world and ideal for distributing open-source software, but consuming from it blindly is a supply-chain risk — packages can be removed without warning, typo-squatted under a deceptively similar name, or compromised at the source. A private repository requires authentication, supports fine-grained access control and integrated vulnerability scanning, and is where an organization stores its proprietary builds and vetted internal artifacts.</p><p>A very common and exam-relevant pattern is a private mirror or proxy that caches approved public packages, so builds remain reproducible even if an upstream package disappears, and so every external dependency passes a scan before it enters the build. Promoting an artifact to that private registry is a routine pipeline step:</p><pre><code>docker tag app:latest registry.example.com/team/app:2.4.0\ndocker push registry.example.com/team/app:2.4.0   # to the private registry</code></pre><h3>Versioning, immutability, and retention</h3><p>Artifacts must be <em>versioned</em> so that any deployment can be traced to an exact build and reproduced or rolled back. The two common schemes are semantic versions such as <code>2.4.0</code> for human-facing releases and commit-hash or build-number tags for internal traceability; many pipelines apply both, tagging an image with the release version and the originating commit SHA. Critically, a published version should be <em>immutable</em> — once <code>app:2.4.0</code> is pushed it must never be overwritten with different bytes, because consumers and rollback procedures assume that a version label always means the same thing. Reusing the mutable <code>latest</code> tag in production is an anti-pattern for exactly this reason: it makes deployments non-reproducible and rollbacks unreliable. Repositories also enforce <em>retention policies</em> to control storage cost, keeping all released versions and recent builds while pruning old, untagged, or superseded artifacts on a schedule.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>EXAM TIP</div>Know the package-format-to-OS mapping cold: RPM means the Red Hat family, .deb means Debian and Ubuntu. ZIP and tar are archives, not OS packages, and a flat file is a single self-contained deliverable. Remember the build-once principle: the artifact promoted to production should be byte-for-byte the one that passed testing, and private registries add authentication, access control, and scanning that public ones do not.</div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Integration of Systems: Event-Driven Architecture", body:"<p>Cloud applications are rarely monoliths; they are constellations of services that must exchange data reliably and at scale. There are two broad styles of integration. <em>Synchronous request/response</em> has a caller send a request and block, waiting for a reply — simple to reason about but tightly coupled and fragile, because the caller fails or stalls whenever the callee is slow or down. <em>Asynchronous messaging</em> lets components communicate without blocking, decoupling their availability and pace from one another. <span class='keyterm'>Event-driven architecture</span> (EDA) is the asynchronous pattern in which components react to <em>events</em> — immutable notifications that something significant has happened — rather than calling each other directly. EDA is foundational to scalable cloud design and underpins serverless platforms, streaming analytics, and microservice choreography.</p><h3>Producers, consumers, and brokers</h3><p>In EDA a <span class='keyterm'>producer</span> emits an event — for example <code>OrderPlaced</code>, carrying the order id and total — to a <span class='keyterm'>message broker</span> or event bus such as Apache Kafka, RabbitMQ, or a managed cloud service like AWS SNS/SQS, Azure Service Bus, or AWS EventBridge. One or more <span class='keyterm'>consumers</span> subscribe and process the event independently and at their own pace. Crucially, the producer neither knows nor cares who consumes the event, which yields <span class='keyterm'>loose coupling</span>: you can add a new consumer — say, a fraud-detection service or a data-warehouse loader — without touching the producer at all. This is the architectural property that lets large systems evolve without coordinated, lock-step deployments across every team.</p><h3>Topologies: pub/sub versus queues</h3><p>Two messaging topologies recur, and the exam expects you to tell them apart. In <span class='keyterm'>publish/subscribe</span> (pub/sub), each event is delivered to <em>every</em> interested subscriber, which is ideal for fan-out notifications where many independent systems each need to react to the same event. In a <span class='keyterm'>message queue</span>, each message is delivered to exactly <em>one</em> consumer from a pool of competing workers, which is ideal for distributing a workload so it can be processed in parallel. Brokers add durability (events persist until acknowledged, surviving a consumer crash), buffering (absorbing traffic spikes so a downstream service is never overwhelmed), ordering guarantees within a partition, and in log-based systems like Kafka the ability to <em>replay</em> a stream of past events to rebuild state from scratch.</p><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>Publish/Subscribe</th><th>Message Queue</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Delivery</td><td>To every subscriber</td><td>To one consumer</td></tr><tr><td>Use case</td><td>Fan-out notifications</td><td>Work distribution</td></tr><tr><td>Scaling</td><td>Add subscribers</td><td>Add competing workers</td></tr><tr><td>Example</td><td>AWS SNS, Kafka topic</td><td>AWS SQS, RabbitMQ queue</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Why EDA fits the cloud, and what it costs</h3><p>Because consumers process events at their own pace, EDA naturally smooths load: a sudden burst of orders fills the queue, and workers drain it as fast as they can autoscale, rather than overwhelming a downstream database all at once. It improves resilience — if a consumer is temporarily down, messages wait safely in the broker rather than being lost — and it enables independent scaling of each component, so a heavy analytics consumer can scale out without affecting the lean checkout path. The cost is added complexity: the system becomes <em>eventually consistent</em> rather than immediately consistent, debugging spans asynchronous hops that are harder to trace end to end, and because most brokers guarantee <em>at-least-once</em> delivery, the same message may arrive more than once. Consumers must therefore be designed to be <span class='keyterm'>idempotent</span> — processing a duplicate event must produce no additional effect, typically by recording the ids of events already handled and skipping repeats.</p><blockquote>In an event-driven system, the design question shifts from <em>who do I call?</em> to <em>what just happened, and who cares?</em></blockquote><h3>Handling failure: dead-letter queues and the saga pattern</h3><p>Asynchronous systems need deliberate patterns for the messages that cannot be processed. A <span class='keyterm'>dead-letter queue</span> (DLQ) is a side queue where the broker routes a message after it has failed processing some configured number of times, so a single poison message does not block the main queue or get retried forever; engineers later inspect the DLQ to diagnose and replay or discard the failures. Because a single business transaction may now span several services connected only by events, distributed consistency is handled with the <span class='keyterm'>saga pattern</span>: instead of one big atomic transaction, the workflow is a chain of local steps, each of which has a compensating action that undoes it if a later step fails. If payment succeeds but shipping cannot be arranged, a compensating event triggers a refund. These patterns are what make eventual consistency operationally safe rather than merely a theoretical trade-off, and recognizing the terms DLQ and saga marks the difference between knowing EDA exists and knowing how to run it.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>SCENARIO</div>A checkout service slows to a crawl during flash sales because it synchronously calls inventory, email, and analytics in line, so the slowest dependency dictates the user's wait. Re-architecting it to publish an OrderPlaced event lets each downstream service consume asynchronously, so checkout returns immediately and the traffic spike is absorbed by the broker rather than by the user's browser.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>EXAM TIP</div>Associate EDA with the keywords loose coupling, asynchronous, scalability, and resilience. Pub/sub fans an event out to many subscribers; a queue distributes work to one consumer at a time. Expect at-least-once delivery, so consumers must be idempotent to tolerate duplicate messages.</div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"Web Services: REST, SOAP, and RPC", body:"<p>A <span class='keyterm'>web service</span> exposes functionality over a network using web protocols so that programs, not people, can consume it. It is the contract by which one system asks another to do something or return data, and it is the glue of every multi-tier cloud application and integration. Three families dominate, and the exam expects you to tell them apart by architectural style, data format, contract strictness, and best-fit use case. Understanding each also means understanding the trade-offs that drive a team to choose one over another, because there is rarely a single right answer divorced from context.</p><h3>REST</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>REST</span> (Representational State Transfer) is an architectural style, not a wire protocol. It models everything as a <em>resource</em> addressed by a URL and manipulated with the standard HTTP verbs: <code>GET</code> reads, <code>POST</code> creates, <code>PUT</code> and <code>PATCH</code> update, and <code>DELETE</code> removes. REST is <em>stateless</em> — each request carries everything the server needs to process it, with no server-side session — which makes it horizontally scalable, since any server behind a load balancer can handle any request. It typically exchanges JSON, returns meaningful HTTP status codes (200 OK, 201 Created, 404 Not Found, 500 Server Error), and leverages standard HTTP caching. Its simplicity and reliance on plain HTTP make it the default choice for public cloud APIs.</p><pre><code>GET /api/v1/orders/4821 HTTP/1.1\nHost: api.example.com\nAuthorization: Bearer eyJhbGci...\nAccept: application/json\n\nHTTP/1.1 200 OK\nContent-Type: application/json\n\n{\n  'id': 4821,\n  'status': 'shipped',\n  'total': 79.95\n}</code></pre><h3>SOAP</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>SOAP</span> (Simple Object Access Protocol) is a strict, XML-based protocol with a formal, machine-readable contract called a <span class='keyterm'>WSDL</span> (Web Services Description Language). Every message is XML wrapped in an <code>&lt;Envelope&gt;</code> with a header and a body. SOAP is verbose, but in exchange it offers built-in enterprise standards: WS-Security for message-level encryption and signing, WS-AtomicTransaction for distributed transactions, and WS-ReliableMessaging for guaranteed delivery. These guarantees are why SOAP persists in banking, healthcare, payment processing, and legacy enterprise integrations, where formal contracts and message-level security matter more than brevity or developer convenience.</p><h3>RPC</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>RPC</span> (Remote Procedure Call) makes a remote function look like a local one: the client calls something like <code>getOrder(4821)</code> and the framework marshals the arguments, sends them across the network, and unmarshals the return value, hiding the network from the caller. Modern variants such as <span class='keyterm'>gRPC</span> use binary Protocol Buffers over HTTP/2, supporting bidirectional streaming and very low overhead, which makes them popular for fast internal service-to-service communication inside a microservice mesh. The trade-off is that RPC is more tightly coupled to the function signature than REST is to a resource, so contract changes ripple more readily out to clients.</p><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>REST</th><th>SOAP</th><th>GraphQL</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Style</td><td>Resource / HTTP verbs</td><td>XML protocol</td><td>Query language</td></tr><tr><td>Data format</td><td>Usually JSON</td><td>XML only</td><td>JSON</td></tr><tr><td>Contract</td><td>Optional (OpenAPI)</td><td>Strict (WSDL)</td><td>Strong (schema)</td></tr><tr><td>State</td><td>Stateless</td><td>Can be stateful</td><td>Stateless</td></tr><tr><td>Endpoints</td><td>Many (per resource)</td><td>One (per operation set)</td><td>One</td></tr><tr><td>Over/under-fetch</td><td>Common</td><td>Common</td><td>Avoided</td></tr><tr><td>Best fit</td><td>Public web APIs</td><td>Enterprise / legacy</td><td>Flexible clients</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Choosing among them</h3><p>The practical decision usually comes down to context. Reach for REST when building a broad public API that many unknown clients will consume over plain HTTP, because its conventions are universally understood and its caching and tooling are mature. Reach for SOAP when integrating with an enterprise or government partner whose contract demands WS-Security, formal schemas, or transactional guarantees. Reach for RPC, especially gRPC, when two services you control need to talk fast and frequently inside your own network and you value raw performance and streaming over universal accessibility. The exam rewards matching the technology to these cues rather than treating any one as universally superior.</p><h3>Cross-cutting concerns: auth, versioning, and idempotency</h3><p>Regardless of style, production web services share several concerns the exam may touch. <em>Authentication and authorization</em> typically ride on bearer tokens — an OAuth 2.0 access token or a JWT in the <code>Authorization</code> header for REST and GraphQL, or WS-Security headers for SOAP — so the service can identify and permit the caller. <em>Versioning</em> lets an API evolve without breaking existing clients: REST commonly versions in the URL path (<code>/api/v1/</code>) or a header, while GraphQL leans on additive schema changes and field deprecation instead of version numbers. <em>Idempotency</em> matters because networks retry: a <code>GET</code> is naturally safe to repeat, a <code>PUT</code> or <code>DELETE</code> is idempotent by design (repeating it leaves the same end state), but a <code>POST</code> that creates a resource is not, so well-built APIs accept an idempotency key the client supplies so a retried create does not produce a duplicate. <em>Rate limiting</em> protects the backend by capping how many requests a client may make in a window, returning <code>429 Too Many Requests</code> when the limit is exceeded. In a microservice estate these concerns are frequently centralized in an <span class='keyterm'>API gateway</span> that sits in front of the services and handles authentication, rate limiting, routing, and request logging in one place, so each service does not reimplement them.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>EXAM TIP</div>Memorize the recognition cues: JSON over plain HTTP verbs against resource URLs is REST; rigid XML envelopes with a WSDL and WS-Security is SOAP; calling a remote function by name (often gRPC with protobuf over HTTP/2) is RPC. Statelessness is a REST hallmark; a WSDL contract is a SOAP hallmark.</div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"GraphQL and Real-Time WebSockets", body:"<p>Two newer integration technologies exist precisely because classic REST falls short in specific ways. <span class='keyterm'>GraphQL</span> solves the twin problems of over-fetching and under-fetching data, while <span class='keyterm'>WebSockets</span> solve REST's inability to let a server push data to a client without first being asked. Both appear by name in the CV0-004 objectives, and both reward you for understanding the exact limitation they were invented to overcome — that understanding is usually the key to picking the right answer.</p><h3>GraphQL</h3><p>GraphQL is a query language for APIs in which the <em>client</em> specifies exactly which fields it wants from a single endpoint, and the server returns precisely that shape of data — no more, no less. Consider the REST problem it fixes. A REST client fetching an order screen might receive an order object stuffed with thirty fields it does not need (<span class='keyterm'>over-fetching</span>, wasting bandwidth and battery on mobile), or it might have to call <code>/orders/4821</code>, then <code>/customers/55</code>, then <code>/customers/55/address</code> just to assemble one view (<span class='keyterm'>under-fetching</span>, paying for multiple round trips). GraphQL collapses all of that into one request whose response mirrors the query exactly:</p><pre><code>POST /graphql HTTP/1.1\nContent-Type: application/json\n\n{\n  'query': 'query { order(id: 4821) { status total customer { name address { city } } } }'\n}\n\nHTTP/1.1 200 OK\n{\n  'data': {\n    'order': {\n      'status': 'shipped',\n      'total': 79.95,\n      'customer': { 'name': 'A. Patel', 'address': { 'city': 'Austin' } }\n    }\n  }\n}</code></pre><p>The single request walks the graph from order to customer to address in one round trip — something that would require three separate REST calls. GraphQL APIs are described by a strongly typed <em>schema</em>, so clients and tooling know in advance every type and field available, enabling rich autocomplete, validation, and self-documenting explorers. The trade-offs are real: HTTP caching is harder because almost everything is a <code>POST</code> to one URL rather than a cacheable <code>GET</code>, server-side resolvers add complexity, and a malicious or careless client can craft a deeply nested, expensive query — so production GraphQL services impose query depth limits, cost analysis, and timeouts to protect the backend.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Concern</th><th>REST</th><th>GraphQL</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Endpoints</td><td>Many</td><td>One</td></tr><tr><td>Data shape</td><td>Fixed by server</td><td>Chosen by client</td></tr><tr><td>Over/under-fetch</td><td>Common</td><td>Avoided</td></tr><tr><td>HTTP caching</td><td>Easy (GET)</td><td>Harder (POST)</td></tr><tr><td>Round trips for nested data</td><td>Several</td><td>One</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>WebSockets</h3><p>HTTP is fundamentally request/response: the client must ask before the server may speak, so delivering live updates over plain HTTP means wasteful <em>polling</em> — asking again and again whether anything has changed, burning bandwidth and CPU on mostly empty answers. <span class='keyterm'>WebSockets</span> solve this by upgrading a single HTTP connection into a persistent, full-duplex channel over which either side can send messages at any time with very little per-message overhead. This is the foundation of live dashboards, chat, multiplayer games, collaborative document editors, IoT telemetry, and streaming price tickers — any case where the server must push data the instant it changes rather than waiting to be polled.</p><p>The connection begins as an ordinary HTTP request carrying an <code>Upgrade</code> header, then switches protocols:</p><pre><code>GET /live HTTP/1.1\nHost: api.example.com\nUpgrade: websocket\nConnection: Upgrade\nSec-WebSocket-Key: dGhlIHNhbXBsZSBub25jZQ==\nSec-WebSocket-Version: 13</code></pre><p>After the server replies with <code>101 Switching Protocols</code>, the underlying TCP connection stays open and frames flow in both directions until either side closes it. Compared with polling a REST endpoint every few seconds, a WebSocket delivers updates with near-zero latency and a fraction of the network and CPU cost. The trade-off is that long-lived connections complicate load balancing and horizontal scaling, since the server must track per-connection state rather than treating each request as independent and disposable.</p><h3>Choosing a real-time approach</h3><p>WebSockets are not the only way to push data, and the exam may contrast the options. <em>Short polling</em> has the client request updates on a fixed timer; it is trivial to implement but wasteful and high-latency. <em>Long polling</em> holds each request open until the server has something to say, approximating push over plain HTTP but still paying connection-setup overhead per message. <em>Server-Sent Events</em> (SSE) provide a lightweight, one-way stream from server to client over a single HTTP connection — perfect for a live feed or notification ticker where the client never needs to push back, and simpler than a full WebSocket. WebSockets remain the right choice when communication must be genuinely <em>bidirectional</em> and low-latency, such as chat or collaborative editing where both ends send continuously. The decision is therefore about directionality and frequency: SSE for one-way streams, WebSockets for two-way interaction, and polling only when nothing better is available. Note too that GraphQL itself addresses real-time needs through <em>subscriptions</em>, which are typically implemented over a WebSocket so that a client can declaratively subscribe to a stream of updates using the same schema and query language it already uses for ordinary reads.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>EXAM TIP</div>If a question mentions clients needing exactly the fields they ask for, eliminating over- and under-fetching from a single endpoint, the answer is GraphQL. If it mentions real-time, bidirectional, server push, or a persistent full-duplex connection, the answer is WebSockets. Plain REST is the wrong answer to any server-push or real-time requirement.</div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"DevOps Tools: Provisioning and Configuration", body:"<p>The CV0-004 objectives name a specific toolset, and you are expected to know what each tool does and, just as importantly, when to reach for it versus its neighbors. This section covers the infrastructure-provisioning and configuration-management tools and the version-control foundation beneath them; containers, orchestration, CI engines, and observability follow in the next two sections. The unifying theme is <span class='keyterm'>infrastructure as code</span> (IaC): describing infrastructure and configuration in version-controlled text so that environments are reproducible, reviewable, and auditable rather than hand-built, snowflake-unique, and undocumented.</p><h3>Terraform — infrastructure provisioning</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Terraform</span> is an infrastructure-as-code tool that <em>provisions</em> cloud resources — virtual networks, subnets, VMs, databases, load balancers, DNS records — from declarative configuration written in HCL. It is <em>declarative</em>: you describe the desired end state and Terraform computes the precise set of create, update, and delete actions needed to reach it, recording what currently exists in a <span class='keyterm'>state file</span> that it consults on every run. It is cloud-agnostic, using pluggable <em>providers</em> for AWS, Azure, GCP, Kubernetes, and hundreds of other platforms, so the same workflow and language manage a multi-cloud estate.</p><pre><code>resource 'aws_instance' 'web' {\n  ami           = 'ami-0abcd1234'\n  instance_type = 't3.micro'\n  tags = {\n    Name = 'web-server'\n  }\n}</code></pre><p>The workflow is <code>terraform init</code> (download providers), <code>terraform plan</code> (preview exactly what will change), and <code>terraform apply</code> (enact it). The plan step is a key safety feature: it shows every addition, change, and destruction before anything happens, so a reviewer can catch a configuration error that would otherwise quietly replace or delete a production database. Because the desired state is code stored in Git, the identical configuration rebuilds an identical environment in another region or account, which is how teams stand up matching dev, staging, and production estates with confidence.</p><h3>Ansible — configuration management</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Ansible</span> operates one layer up from provisioning: it <em>configures</em> machines that already exist, installing packages, templating files, managing users, and starting services to bring each host to a desired state. It is <em>agentless</em>, connecting over ordinary SSH (or WinRM on Windows), so there is no daemon to install and maintain on managed nodes — a meaningful operational advantage at scale. Its instructions are written as YAML <span class='keyterm'>playbooks</span> composed of tasks, and those tasks are designed to be <span class='keyterm'>idempotent</span> — running a playbook a second time makes no changes if the system is already in the desired state, which makes Ansible safe to run repeatedly as a continuous enforcement mechanism.</p><pre><code>- hosts: webservers\n  become: true\n  tasks:\n    - name: Install nginx\n      apt:\n        name: nginx\n        state: present\n    - name: Deploy site config\n      template:\n        src: site.conf.j2\n        dest: /etc/nginx/conf.d/site.conf\n    - name: Ensure nginx is running\n      service:\n        name: nginx\n        state: started\n        enabled: true</code></pre><h3>Git and GitOps — the foundation</h3><p>Underpinning all of these is <span class='keyterm'>Git</span>, the version-control system covered earlier in this domain. Every Terraform configuration, Ansible playbook, and pipeline definition belongs in Git so that infrastructure changes flow through the same review-and-pipeline discipline as application code. This practice is called <span class='keyterm'>GitOps</span>: the Git repository is the declared source of truth for the system, and an automated agent continuously reconciles the live environment to match what the repository says it should be. A change to infrastructure becomes a pull request, reviewed and merged like any other, after which automation applies it — and any manual drift in the live environment is detected and corrected back to the declared state.</p><h3>Imperative versus declarative, and managing state</h3><p>A recurring theme worth making explicit is the contrast between <em>imperative</em> and <em>declarative</em> approaches. An imperative script says <em>how</em> to do something step by step (create this VM, then open that port, then install this package) and breaks if run twice or if the starting state differs. A declarative tool says <em>what</em> the end state should be and lets the tool figure out the steps, which is why both Terraform and Ansible are declarative and idempotent — you can run them repeatedly and converge on the same result. The cost of Terraform's power is its <span class='keyterm'>state file</span>, which records the mapping between your configuration and the real resources it created. That state must be stored in a shared, locked backend (such as an S3 bucket with a lock table) so that a whole team works against one consistent view, and it must be protected because it can contain sensitive values. Mismanaged state — lost, stale, or edited by two people at once — is one of the most common sources of real-world Terraform pain, which is why remote state with locking is considered a baseline practice rather than an optimization. Closely related tools round out this space: Packer builds golden machine images that Terraform then provisions, while Puppet and Chef are agent-based configuration managers that occupy the same niche as Ansible but pull desired state from a central server rather than pushing over SSH.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Layer</th><th>Model</th><th>Agent?</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Terraform</td><td>Provisioning (create infra)</td><td>Declarative</td><td>Agentless</td></tr><tr><td>Ansible</td><td>Configuration (set up hosts)</td><td>Declarative, idempotent</td><td>Agentless (SSH)</td></tr><tr><td>Git</td><td>Source of truth</td><td>Versioned history</td><td>n/a</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>EXAM TIP</div>Draw the line clearly: Terraform <em>provisions</em> infrastructure — it creates the servers, networks, and databases — while Ansible <em>configures</em> what runs on machines that already exist. Both are declarative and idempotent and both are agentless, but they operate at different layers, and you often use them together: Terraform builds the VM, then Ansible configures the software on it.</div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"DevOps Tools: Containers, Orchestration, and CI Engines", body:"<p>Continuing the named toolset, this section covers packaging applications into containers, orchestrating those containers at scale across a cluster, and the engines that drive the CI/CD pipelines themselves. These tools are the operational heart of modern cloud delivery: they take the artifact a pipeline builds and turn it into reliably running, self-healing, scalable software, and the exam expects you to know the distinct role each one plays.</p><h3>Docker — containerization</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Docker</span> packages an application together with all of its dependencies into a portable <span class='keyterm'>container image</span> that runs identically on any host with a compatible container runtime, eliminating the it-works-on-my-machine problem. Containers share the host kernel and isolate processes with namespaces and cgroups, so they are far lighter than virtual machines and start in seconds rather than minutes. The image is defined declaratively by a <code>Dockerfile</code>, and each instruction creates a cached layer, so rebuilds are fast when only later layers change:</p><pre><code>FROM python:3.12-slim\nWORKDIR /app\nCOPY requirements.txt .\nRUN pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt\nCOPY . .\nEXPOSE 8000\nCMD ['gunicorn', '-b', '0.0.0.0:8000', 'app:app']</code></pre><p>Instruction ordering matters for cache efficiency: copying and installing dependencies <em>before</em> copying the application source means a routine code change does not invalidate the expensive dependency-install layer, so most rebuilds reuse it. <code>docker build</code> produces the image, <code>docker run</code> starts a container from it, and <code>docker push</code> sends it to a registry for distribution.</p><h3>Kubernetes — orchestration</h3><p>Docker runs containers on one host; <span class='keyterm'>Kubernetes</span> (k8s) <em>orchestrates</em> them across a whole cluster of machines. It schedules containers onto nodes, restarts ones that crash, scales the count up and down to meet demand, performs rolling updates and rollbacks, and provides built-in service discovery and load balancing. Workloads are declared as YAML manifests; a <span class='keyterm'>Deployment</span> tells Kubernetes to keep a desired number of identical replica <span class='keyterm'>Pods</span> running, and a controller continuously reconciles reality to that declaration:</p><pre><code>apiVersion: apps/v1\nkind: Deployment\nmetadata:\n  name: web\nspec:\n  replicas: 3\n  selector:\n    matchLabels:\n      app: web\n  template:\n    metadata:\n      labels:\n        app: web\n    spec:\n      containers:\n        - name: web\n          image: registry.example.com/app:1.4.0\n          ports:\n            - containerPort: 8000</code></pre><p>If a node dies, Kubernetes reschedules its Pods elsewhere to maintain the declared three replicas; if you change the image tag and re-apply the manifest, it performs a rolling update, replacing Pods gradually so the service stays available throughout. A separate <em>Service</em> object gives the Pods a stable virtual IP and load-balances traffic across them, because individual Pods are ephemeral and may be replaced at any time. This reconcile loop — observe actual state, compare to desired state, act to close the gap — is the essence of orchestration.</p><h3>CI engines: Jenkins and GitHub Actions</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Jenkins</span> is a mature, self-hosted automation server with an enormous plugin ecosystem; pipelines are defined in a <code>Jenkinsfile</code> and run on infrastructure you own and manage, which gives maximum control and on-premises capability at the cost of patching and maintaining the server yourself. <span class='keyterm'>GitHub Actions</span> is a hosted CI/CD service tightly integrated with GitHub, where workflows live as YAML in the repository and run on managed runners with no server to maintain. Choose Jenkins when you need full control, custom plugins, air-gapped or strict on-prem hosting; choose GitHub Actions for zero-maintenance, repository-native automation that is up and running in minutes.</p><h3>Container registries and the image lifecycle</h3><p>The three tools form a clear lifecycle that the exam may probe end to end. A CI engine such as GitHub Actions or Jenkins builds a Docker image from a Dockerfile, tags it with a version and commit SHA, and pushes it to a <em>container registry</em> like Amazon ECR, Azure Container Registry, or a private Harbor instance. Kubernetes then pulls that exact tagged image from the registry when it schedules the Deployment's Pods onto nodes. This is the build-once-deploy-many principle made concrete: the image that the pipeline tested is byte-for-byte the image Kubernetes runs in production, identified by an immutable tag rather than the mutable <code>latest</code>. Registries also participate in security, scanning images for OS-level CVEs on push and refusing to serve images that fail policy. Recognizing that the CI engine produces the image, the registry stores it, and the orchestrator consumes it ties the entire domain together and explains why these tools are taught as a set rather than in isolation. Around this core sit related technologies worth knowing by name: Helm packages Kubernetes manifests into versioned, parameterized charts for repeatable deployment, while managed offerings such as Amazon EKS, Azure AKS, and Google GKE run the Kubernetes control plane for you so teams consume orchestration without operating the cluster themselves.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Role</th><th>Reach for it when</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Docker</td><td>Containerization</td><td>Packaging an app plus its deps</td></tr><tr><td>Kubernetes</td><td>Orchestration</td><td>Running containers at scale, self-healing</td></tr><tr><td>Jenkins</td><td>CI/CD engine (self-hosted)</td><td>On-prem, plugin-heavy pipelines, full control</td></tr><tr><td>GitHub Actions</td><td>CI/CD engine (hosted)</td><td>Repo-native, low-maintenance automation</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>SCENARIO</div>A service running as a single Docker container on one VM keeps going down when that VM reboots, and traffic spikes overwhelm it. Moving the image into a Kubernetes Deployment with three replicas and a horizontal autoscaler gives self-healing — crashed Pods restart automatically and lost nodes are rescheduled — plus elastic scaling without manual intervention.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>EXAM TIP</div>Docker builds and runs an individual container; Kubernetes manages many containers across many hosts. If a scenario calls for self-healing, automatic scaling, rolling updates, or scheduling across a cluster, the answer is Kubernetes, not Docker alone. Jenkins is self-hosted and plugin-rich; GitHub Actions is hosted and repo-native.</div>"}
);
CLOUDPLUS.reading[5].push(
  {heading:"DevOps Tools: Observability with ELK and Grafana", body:"<p>Operating cloud systems at scale demands <span class='keyterm'>observability</span> — the ability to understand a system's internal state purely from its external outputs. Observability rests on three pillars: <em>logs</em> (discrete event records, the what-happened), <em>metrics</em> (numeric measurements over time, the how-much), and <em>traces</em> (the path of a single request across many services, the where). The CV0-004 objectives name two cornerstone tools: the ELK stack, which centralizes and searches logs, and Grafana, which visualizes metrics and drives alerting. In a distributed cloud system these are not luxuries — when a single user request crosses ten microservices, no individual machine's log or graph tells the whole story, so centralized observability is the only practical way to diagnose problems before customers do.</p><h3>The ELK / Elastic Stack</h3><p>The <span class='keyterm'>ELK stack</span> is a trio of complementary tools for centralized logging, and you should be able to attribute each role to the correct letter without hesitation. <span class='keyterm'>Logstash</span> is the ingestion and processing pipeline: it collects log data from many heterogeneous sources, parses and transforms it (extracting fields, normalizing timestamps, enriching records with geolocation or user context), and forwards the structured result onward. <span class='keyterm'>Elasticsearch</span> is the distributed search and analytics engine that indexes and stores those logs so they can be queried in milliseconds across terabytes of data — effectively full-text search over your entire fleet's logs at once. <span class='keyterm'>Kibana</span> is the web user interface that lets engineers search, filter, aggregate, and visualize the indexed data, building dashboards and running ad-hoc queries during an incident.</p><p>In modern deployments a lightweight shipper called a <em>Beat</em> (for example Filebeat) often runs on each host and forwards logs to the central pipeline, sometimes replacing Logstash for simple collection while Logstash handles heavier transformation — hence the broader product name <em>Elastic Stack</em>. The value is stark: rather than SSHing into a dozen servers and grepping local files by hand, an engineer issues one Kibana query and sees every matching log line across the whole environment, correlated by time.</p><h3>Grafana — metrics dashboards and alerting</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Grafana</span> is an open-source visualization and dashboarding platform, and a crucial point for the exam is that it does <em>not</em> store the data itself. Instead it connects to one or more <em>data sources</em> — most famously the time-series database <span class='keyterm'>Prometheus</span>, but also Elasticsearch, cloud monitoring services like CloudWatch, and SQL databases — and renders their metrics as graphs, gauges, heatmaps, and tables on richly customizable dashboards. Grafana also provides <span class='keyterm'>alerting</span>: you define a rule such as CPU above 90 percent for five minutes or error rate above one percent, and Grafana evaluates it continuously and notifies an on-call engineer through email, Slack, PagerDuty, or a generic webhook the moment the threshold is breached.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Pillar</th><th>Role</th><th>Stores data?</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Logstash / Beats</td><td>Logs</td><td>Collect, parse, ship</td><td>No (pipeline)</td></tr><tr><td>Elasticsearch</td><td>Logs</td><td>Index and search</td><td>Yes</td></tr><tr><td>Kibana</td><td>Logs</td><td>Visualize and query logs</td><td>No (UI)</td></tr><tr><td>Grafana</td><td>Metrics</td><td>Dashboards and alerts</td><td>No (queries sources)</td></tr><tr><td>Prometheus</td><td>Metrics</td><td>Scrape and store time series</td><td>Yes</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Logs and metrics together</h3><p>Logs and metrics answer different questions and are most powerful in combination. Metrics tell you <em>that</em> something is wrong and roughly where — a latency graph spikes, an error-rate gauge turns red — quickly and cheaply, because they are compact numbers aggregated over time. Logs then tell you <em>what</em> and <em>why</em>, because they carry the detailed event records, stack traces, and request identifiers needed to pinpoint the cause. The everyday operational loop is to notice a problem on a Grafana dashboard and then pivot to Kibana to read the relevant logs for the same service and the same time window.</p><h3>Tracing, SLOs, and alert quality</h3><p>The third observability pillar, <em>distributed tracing</em>, completes the picture by following a single request as it hops across services, with each hop recorded as a timed <em>span</em> sharing a common trace id. Tracing tools such as Jaeger or Tempo answer the question metrics and logs cannot — exactly which service in a long chain added the latency — and they integrate into Grafana dashboards alongside the other signals. Observability also feeds <span class='keyterm'>service level objectives</span> (SLOs): explicit targets such as 99.9 percent of requests succeeding within 300 milliseconds, measured directly from the metrics, with an <em>error budget</em> that quantifies how much failure is tolerable before releases are paused to focus on reliability. Finally, alert quality is its own discipline: alerts should fire on user-facing symptoms rather than every internal blip, should be actionable (each one tied to a runbook), and should avoid the noise that causes alert fatigue and trains responders to ignore their pagers. Good observability is judged not by how much it collects but by how quickly it lets an engineer find and fix what matters.</p><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>SCENARIO</div>Users report intermittent timeouts. The on-call engineer opens a Grafana dashboard, sees p99 latency spiking on one service while every other service is flat, then pivots to Kibana and searches that service's error logs for the same five-minute window, finding repeated database-connection-pool-exhausted entries. Metrics revealed that something was wrong; logs revealed exactly what.</div><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>EXAM TIP</div>Map each ELK letter to its job: Elasticsearch stores and searches, Logstash ingests and transforms, Kibana visualizes. Pair ELK with logs and Grafana with metrics dashboards and alerting, and remember that Grafana stores nothing itself — it queries data sources such as Prometheus.</div>"}
);
